HEADWORD: Renitency
<hw>Re*ni"ten*cy</hw> <pr>(-t<it>e</it>-s?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[Cf. F. <ets>r⟦eacute⟧nitence</ets>.]</ety> <def>The state or
quality of being renitent; resistance; reluctance.</def>
<rj><au>Sterne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We find a <qex>renitency</qex> in ourselves to ascribe life and
irritability to the cold and motionless fibers of plants.</q>
<rj><qau>E. Darwin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Renitent</ent>⟦br⟧
